i. Create diagnostic plots for the regression and interpret them.

https://www.hackerearth.com/blog/developers/beginners-guide-regression-analysis-plot-interpretations/

A: Residual vs. Fitted Values Plot (Upper left)

Ideally, this plot shouldn’t show any pattern. But if you see any shape (curve, U shape), it suggests non-linearity in the data set. In addition, if you see a funnel shape pattern, it suggests your data is suffering from heteroskedasticity, i.e. the error terms have non-constant variance.

In our case, it shows linearity in the data set with most of the dot around the linear line.

Normality Q-Q Plot (Upper right)

As the name suggests, this plot is used to determine the normal distribution of errors. It uses standardized values of residuals. Ideally, this plot should show a straight line. If you find a curved, distorted line, then your residuals have a non-normal distribution (problematic situation).

In our case, it also shows a quite linear line which suggests that it is a normal distribution.

Scale Location Plot (Lower left)

This plot is also useful to determine heteroskedasticity. Ideally, this plot shouldn’t show any pattern. Presence of a pattern determine heteroskedasticity. Don’t forget to corroborate the findings of this plot with the funnel shape in residual vs. fitted values.

In our case, it also shows a linear line which suggests that it do not present a heteroskedasticity (Heteroscedasticity is a problem because ordinary least squares (OLS) regression assumes that all residuals are drawn from a population that has a constant variance).

Residuals vs. Leverage plots (Lower right)

The Residuals vs. Leverage plots helps you identify influential data points on your model. Outliers can be influential, though they don’t necessarily have to it and some points within a normal range in your model could be very influential.

In our case, there is not a outlier present.

par(mfrow=(c(2,2)))
plot(weilys.lm)

In these cases we can sometimes see strange and even inscrutable patterns in a scatterplot of the data. Sometimes there really is no meaningful relationship between the two variables. Other times, a careful transformation of one or both of the variables can reveal a clear relationship.

3.

The following code shows a function that uses a Monte-Carlo simulation to calculate the posterior probability interpretation of p-values near 0.05 for differing prior probabilities/plausibilities of the null hypothesis.

Use this function to plot a graph of posterior probability versus prior probability from 0.1 to 0.9.

# This function simulates a one-sample experimental design. 
# It generates a set of experimental results where the effect is real 
# and a set of experimental results where the null hypothesis is true.
# Arguments: prior=prior probability that the null is true
# Returns: posterior probability that null is true for p-values near 0.05
pvalue_monte_carlo <- function(prior)
{
# The power of the experiment affects the interpretation of the p-value. We set some example values here.  
n <- 10   # sample size
sigma <- 20.0 # population standard deviation
effect_size <- 20.0 # size of effect of experimental treatment

x <- 0
y <- 0
no_effect <- c()
effect <- c()

for (i in 1:100000) {
  isnull <- sample(c(TRUE,FALSE), 1, prob=c(prior, 1-prior)) # randomly choose either a null or active treatment depending on prior
  if (isnull == TRUE) {     # if treatment has no effect (null is true)
    exp <- rnorm(n, mean=120.0,sd = sigma)
  } else {                  # # if treatment has an effect
    exp <- rnorm(n, mean=120.0-effect_size,sd = sigma)
  }
  pval <- t.test(exp, mu=120)$p.value # one-sample t-test
  if (isnull == TRUE) {     # if treatment has no effect (null is true)
    no_effect[i] <- pval 
  } else {
    effect[i] <- pval
  }
  if (pval < 0.05 && pval >= 0.049) {  # choose p-values near some value
    x <- x + 1              # count how many such p-values there are
    if (isnull == TRUE) {
      y <- y + 1            # of these p-values, for how many was the null hypothesis true
    }
  }  
}
return(y/x)
}
number<-1
sequence<-seq(from=0.1, to=0.9, by=0.1)
priority_probability<-rep(0,9)
for (i in sequence){
    priority_probability[number]<-pvalue_monte_carlo(i)
    #print(i)
    number<-number+1
    #print(number)
}

print("This is the posterior probability")
## [1] "This is the posterior probability"
print(priority_probability)
## [1] 0.03806228 0.10320285 0.11188811 0.20083682 0.23943662 0.32142857
## [7] 0.41317365 0.48611111 0.83464567
combine_pvalue<- data.frame(sequence,priority_probability)
ggplot(data = combine_pvalue, aes(y = priority_probability, x = sequence)) +geom_point() +xlab("Prior Probability") + ylab("Posterior Probability")+ scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(0.1, 0.9, 0.1))

The following code shows a function that uses a Monte-Carlo simulation to return the power of a one-sample t-test.

Add comments describing how the code functions.

Assume that if the drug has an effect size of 20.0 mmHg, then we want a p-value of 0.005 for 80% across replications of the experiment. The population standard deviation is 20 mmHg.

Use this function to plot a graph of power versus sample size from 2 to 20. What sample size do you suggest for this experiment?

Use the power.t.test() function for the power analysis. How does its recommendation compare to the Monte Carlo simulation?

Add comments describing how the code functions.

# Monte Carlo simulation of power of one sample z-test
# arguments: sample_size=n, effect_size=delta, sigma=sd, type1_error=sig.level 
# returns: power
power_monte_carlo <- function(sample_size, effect_size, sigma, type1_error_rate) #input the parameter to calculate the power
{
  pval <- c() #use a vector to store p value
  num_iter <- 10000 # number of iterations for monte_carlo simulation 
  for (i in 1:num_iter) {
    exp <- rnorm(sample_size, mean=effect_size,sd = sigma) # use rnorm to create a data with mean = effect_size and sd = sigma
    pval[i] <- t.test(exp, mu=0)$p.value # one-sample t-test and extract the p-value for the t-test
  }
  type2_error_rate <- sum(pval >= type1_error_rate)/num_iter # type2_error_rate means the probability of failing to   reject a false null hypothesis which means p_value larger than the predefined alpha= 0.005
  return(1-type2_error_rate) # power = 1-type2_error_rate
}

Use this function to plot a graph of power versus sample size from 2 to 20. What sample size do you suggest for this experiment?

A: The power the larger the better. I would say I suggest 20 in our case and larger than 18 at least to meet the 80% requirement.

library(ggplot2)
number<-1
effect_size<-20
type1_error_rate<-0.005
sigma<-20
sample_size<-seq(from=2, to=20, by=1)
power<-rep(0,19)
for (i in sample_size){
  power[number]<-power_monte_carlo(i,effect_size = effect_size,sigma = sigma,type1_error_rate = type1_error_rate)
  #print(i)
  number<-number+1
  #print(number)
}

print(power)
##  [1] 0.0101 0.0208 0.0414 0.0750 0.1144 0.1693 0.2355 0.3095 0.3774 0.4520
## [11] 0.5246 0.5811 0.6450 0.6869 0.7433 0.7904 0.8275 0.8536 0.8818
combine_power<- data.frame(sample_size,power)
ggplot(data = combine_power, aes(y = power, x = sample_size)) +geom_point() +xlab("Sample Size") + ylab("Power")+ scale_x_continuous(breaks=seq(2, 20, 1))
